  "provider": "anthropic",
  "model": "claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
  "response_text": "# Fitness & Diet Plan for Long Commute Lifestyle\n\n## Overview\nThis plan maximizes limited free time while managing energy levels and nutrition around a demanding schedule.\n\n---\n\n## FITNESS STRATEGY\n\n### Commute-Based Activity (30–60 min)\n- **Cycle or run part of the route** (if feasible)\n- **Stand/walk during transit** instead of sitting\n- **Desk stretches** at work (5-min hourly)\n- **Isometric exercises** on public transport (glute squeezes, wall sits mentally)\n\n### Micro-Workouts (15–20 min, 4–5× weekly)\n**Morning (before commute):**\n- 5 min warm-up\n- 10 min circuit: push-ups, bodyweight squats, burpees, planks\n- 5 min cool-down\n\n**Evening (post-commute):**\n- 15 min walk or light yoga to decompress\n\n### Weekend Sessions (45–60 min, 1–2× weekly)\n- Strength training (compound movements)\n- Longer cardio or sports\n- Active recovery (hiking, swimming)\n\n---\n\n## NUTRITION PLAN\n\n### Meal Prep Strategy (2–3 hours Sunday)\nPrep 4–5 days of meals to avoid relying on commute food.\n\n| Meal | Options | Benefit |\n|------|---------|---------|\n| **Breakfast** | Overnight oats, egg muffins, yogurt parfait | Portable, sustained energy |\n| **Snacks** | Nuts, fruit, protein bars, hummus + veggies | Prevents energy crashes |\n| **Lunch** | Grain bowls, wraps, salads in containers | Avoids expensive takeout |\n| **Dinner** | Sheet pan meals, slow cooker recipes, pasta | Minimal prep after commute |\n\n### Daily Hydration & Caffeine\n- **Morning:** Coffee/tea (1 cup max) + water\n- **Commute:** Reusable water bottle (refill 2–3× daily)\n- **Afternoon:** Herbal tea or water (avoid caffeine after 3 PM)\n\n### Sample Daily Eating Schedule\n```\n6:00 AM   Breakfast (200–300 cal)\n8:30 AM   Snack on commute (100–150 cal)\n12:30 PM  Lunch (400–500 cal)\n3:00 PM   Snack (150 cal)\n7:00 PM   Dinner (500–600 cal)\n```\n\n---\n\n## COMMUTE-SPECIFIC TIPS\n\n| Challenge | Solution |\n|-----------|----------|\n| **Sitting too long** | Alternate sitting/standing; do calf raises at stops |\n| **Fatigue** | Eat protein + carbs 1 hour before commute |\n| **Hunger on return** | Pack post-workout snack (banana + nuts) |\n| **Stress eating** | Prep healthy snacks; practice breathing exercises |\n| **Sleep disruption** | Avoid heavy dinners; wind down 1 hour before bed |\n\n---\n\n## WEEKLY SAMPLE SCHEDULE\n\n| Day | Morning | Commute | Evening |\n|-----|---------|---------|---------|\n| **Mon** | 15 min circuit | Walk part of route | 15 min yoga |\n| **Tue** | 5 min stretch | Active transit | Rest |\n| **Wed** | 15 min circuit | Cycle/run if possible | 20 min walk |\n| **Thu** | 5 min stretch | Active transit | Rest |\n| **Fri** | 15 min circuit | Walk part of route | Light activity |\n| **Sat** | 45 min strength training | — | — |\n| **Sun** | Meal prep + 30 min activity | — | Rest |\n\n---\n\n## REALISTIC GOALS (8–12 weeks)\n\n✓ Maintain current fitness (vs. declining)  \n✓ Lose 5–8 lbs if needed  \n✓ Improve energy and sleep quality  \n✓ Build sustainable habits  \n✓ Reduce stress-related eating  \n\n---\n\n## Key Success Factors\n\n1. **Prep everything** — your biggest enemy is convenience food\n2. **Use commute time strategically** — walk/cycle segments count\n3. **Lower intensity, higher frequency** — short workouts beat skipped long ones\n4. **Sleep prioritizes fitness** — aim for 7–8 hours\n5. **Track energy, not just calories** — adjust if constantly exhausted\n\nWould you like specific meal prep recipes or modifications for your commute type?",
